\subsection{Loop quantum cosmological evolution during the Bose-Einstein condensation phase}

In the first-order phase transition, we have constant temperature and pressure,
respectively as $T=T_{{\rm cr}}$ and $p=p_{{\rm cr}}$.
Moreover,    the enthalpy $W=(\rho+p)a^{3}$ and entropy $S=sa^{3}$ are also
conserved quantities. The phase transition begins through a decrease in the density of dark matter and increase in the density of Bose-Einstein
condensed state. This is because the density $\rho^{{\rm cr}}_{\chi}(T_{{\rm cr}})\equiv\rho^{nor}_{\chi}$ is converted to $\rho_{\chi}(T_{{\rm cr}})\equiv\rho^{{\rm BEC}}_{\chi}$ during the phase transition. One may define a  useful time dependent parameter $h(t)$, playing the role of $\rho_{\chi}(t)$, which is called the volume fraction of the matter in the Bose-Einstein condensed phase
\begin{eqnarray}\label{eq44}
